                    <seg corresp="#KR4h0001_tls_042-11a.5" xml:lang="en" resp="#CH" modified="2020-12-02T20:47:30.245+09:00" resp-del="#CH" src-id="KR4h0001-en">▼►▼■► It gets to the point where I do not close my eyes the whole night.1----1Here comes a crucial twist:  Cao refers to himself and his intended readership together.  Note that zúxià 足下 can only be used in letters or letter-like literature.  The word is never used in books to refer to the reader. In no book does the author refer to himself and the readership as a group, as a zámen 咱們 "we".  Cao uses this "congenial we" and creates an almost intellectually/aesthetically conspiratorial intensity of communication which makes this document so fascinating.</seg>
                    <seg corresp="#KR4h0001_tls_042-8a.4" xml:lang="en" resp="#CH" modified="2020-12-02T20:49:37.768+09:00" resp-del="#CH" src-id="KR4h0001-en">►■　Cao Pi speaking:</seg>
                    <seg corresp="#CH1d0955_CHANT_005-1a.10" xml:lang="en" resp="#chris" modified="2020-12-03T09:11:18.137+09:00" resp-del="#chris" src-id="CH1d0955-en-13a1a51a">1.Aversion to wind means a mild cold sensation on the skin at times or upon exposure to wind or draft. It could abate when the patient is not exposed to wind. Both aversion to wind and aversion to cold are common symptoms seen in tai yang disease. Both of them would occur regardless of the presentation of external wind or cold. Neither of them would diminish by adding extra clothing or blankets. The cause for both of them are the failure of the defensive qi to warm the body surface due to attack of wind-cold.</seg>
                    <seg corresp="#CH1d0955_CHANT_005-1a.9" xml:lang="en" resp="#chris" modified="2020-12-03T09:13:48.102+09:00" resp-del="#chris" src-id="CH1d0955-en-13a1a51a">2.A moderate pulse in this line is a literal translation of “緩脉 huán mài,” which is usually done in modern textbooks in Chinese medicine. Jiang Jian-Guo and Li Shu-Pei point out:</seg>
                    <seg corresp="#CH1d0955_CHANT_005-1a.9" xml:lang="en" resp="#chris" modified="2020-12-03T09:14:53.08+09:00" resp-del="#chris" src-id="CH1d0955-en-13a1a51a">2.A moderate pulse in this line is a literal translation of “緩脉 huán mài,” which is usually done in modern textbooks in Chinese medicine. Jiang Jian-Guo and Li Shu-Pei point out: \nThe application of relativity in the pulse diagnosis is one unique approach to the pulse diagnosis in Discussion of Cold Damage; the term “緩脉 huán mài” is the opposite of the term “緊脉 jǐn mài (tight pulse).” [Zhang] Zhong-Jing originally wanted to elucidate the feature of clinical presentation and etiology for shang han syndrome and zhong feng syndrome in tai yang disease by comparing “緩脉 huán mài (a moderate pulse)” with “緊脉 jǐn mài (a tight pulse).” Any pulse that isnot tight can be called “緩脉 huán mài (a moderate pulse).</seg>
                    <seg corresp="#CH1d0955_CHANT_005-2a.5" xml:lang="en" resp="#chris" modified="2020-12-03T09:49:54.688+09:00" resp-del="#chris" src-id="CH1d0955-en-d0a29708">aversion to cold must occur. There is pain over the body, vomiting and a tight pulse at the yin and yang positions. This is called shang han [syndrome].</seg>
                    <seg corresp="#CH1d0955_CHANT_005-2a.3" xml:lang="en" resp="#chris" modified="2020-12-03T09:53:11.882+09:00" resp-del="#chris" src-id="CH1d0955-en-13a1a51a">1.Fever might not present at the very beginning of shang han syndrome in tai yang disease because wind-cold, in which cold predominates, will move slowly to encounter the defensive qi and slowly stagnate the defensive qi while generating a hot feeling on the body surface at the very beginning. Fever will present soon afterward as long as wind-cold completely engages in the defensive qi and obstructs it. Fang You-Zhi offered an insightful explanation for the pathomechanism of fever due to attack of cold in this line. He wrote:</seg>
                    <seg corresp="#CH1d0955_CHANT_005-2a.8" xml:lang="en" resp="#chris" modified="2020-12-03T11:38:24.025+09:00" resp-del="#chris" src-id="CH1d0955-en-13a1a51a">3.A tight pulse at yin and yang position means a tight pulse is felt on the distal, middle and proximal positions. Fang You-Zhi said that “yin refers to the position behind the middle position while yang to the position ahead of the middle position. A tight pulse appearing on all three positions is caused by the rigid attribution of cold.”[[</seg>
                </p>
